            "description": "Render tiddlers matching a filter to a specified ContentType",
            "text": "Render a set of tiddlers matching a filter to separate files of a specified ContentType (defaults to `text/html`) and extension (defaults to `.html`).\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers <filter> <template> <pathname> [<type>] [<extension>] [\"noclean\"]\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--rendertiddlers [!is[system]] $:/core/templates/static.tiddler.html ./static text/plain\n```\n\nBy default, the pathname is resolved relative to the `output` subdirectory of the edition directory. The `--output` command can be used to direct output to a different directory.\n\nAny files in the target directory are deleted unless the ''noclean'' flag is specified. The target directory is recursively created if it is missing.\n"

        "$:/language/Help/server": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/server",
            "description": "Provides an HTTP server interface to TiddlyWiki",
            "text": "The server built in to TiddlyWiki5 is very simple. Although compatible with TiddlyWeb it doesn't support many of the features needed for robust Internet-facing usage.\n\nAt the root, it serves a rendering of a specified tiddler. Away from the root, it serves individual tiddlers encoded in JSON, and supports the basic HTTP operations for `GET`, `PUT` and `DELETE`.\n\n```\n--server <port> <roottiddler> <rendertype> <servetype> <username> <password> <host> <pathprefix>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''port'' - port number to serve from (defaults to \"8080\")\n* ''roottiddler'' - the tiddler to serve at the root (defaults to \"$:/core/save/all\")\n* ''rendertype'' - the content type to which the root tiddler should be rendered (defaults to \"text/plain\")\n* ''servetype'' - the content type with which the root tiddler should be served (defaults to \"text/html\")\n* ''username'' - the default username for signing edits\n* ''password'' - optional password for basic authentication\n* ''host'' - optional hostname to serve from (defaults to \"127.0.0.1\" aka \"localhost\")\n* ''pathprefix'' - optional prefix for paths\n\nIf the password parameter is specified then the browser will prompt the user for the username and password. Note that the password is transmitted in plain text so this implementation isn't suitable for general use.\n\nFor example:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html MyUserName passw0rd\n```\n\nThe username and password can be specified as empty strings if you need to set the hostname or pathprefix and don't want to require a password:\n\n```\n--server 8080 $:/core/save/all text/plain text/html \"\" \"\" 192.168.0.245\n```\n\nTo run multiple TiddlyWiki servers at the same time you'll need to put each one on a different port.\n"
        },
        "$:/language/Help/setfield": {
            "title": "$:/language/Help/setfield",
            "description": "Prepares external tiddlers for use",
            "text": "//Note that this command is experimental and may change or be replaced before being finalised//\n\nSets the specified field of a group of tiddlers to the result of wikifying a template tiddler with the `currentTiddler` variable set to the tiddler.\n\n```\n--setfield <filter> <fieldname> <templatetitle> <rendertype>\n```\n\nThe parameters are:\n\n* ''filter'' - filter identifying the tiddlers to be affected\n* ''fieldname'' - the field to modify (defaults to \"text\")\n* ''templatetitle'' - the tiddler to wikify into the specified field. If blank or missing then the specified field is deleted\n* ''rendertype'' - the text type to render (defaults to \"text/plain\"; \"text/html\" can be used to include HTML tags)\n"

Decrypting your tiddler will restore it to its original state when you encrypted it. This way you can hide the encrypted tiddlers as a \"different\" thing.\n* You can even encrypt images.\n* You can have sensible data in a day to day wiky.\n* I didn't try this, but theoretically you can apply double encryption by encrypting your wiki too."

It resembles the design used by ~GitHub for their \"Fork me on ~GitHub\" ribbons.\n\nThe ribbon can be positioned over any corner, and can incorporate user defined text, colours and a link.\n\nThe CSS stylesheet is adapted from work by Simon Whitaker:\n\nhttps://github.com/simonwhitaker/github-fork-ribbon-css/\n\n[[Source code|https://github.com/Jermolene/TiddlyWiki5/blob/master/plugins/tiddlywiki/github-fork-ribbon]]\n"

''13 Danger Signs of Suicide''

Obviously, there are many warning signs for suicide and this list is not exclusive, but the following are signs to look out for.

# The caller is withdrawn and unable to relate to you or others
# There is a history of suicide in the family or among others close to the caller
# The caller has made previous suicide attempts
# The caller has a definite idea of how to kill him/herself and/or is tidying up affairs
# There is an anxious tone to the caller’s general impression of depression
# The caller is dependent on alcohol or drugs
# The caller has some painful physical illness or long sleep disturbances
# The caller feels useless, for instance following retirement or the moving away of children
# The caller has suffered significant losses and bereavements recently and/or in the past
# The caller feels (or is) isolated, lonely and possibly uprooted and is facing the possibility of having to live with few human contacts
# The caller lacks a comforting philosophy of life such as a supportive religious faith
# The caller has serious financial worries
# Within the cycle of rise and fall in mood, the most dangerous time can often be when the caller is feeling somewhat better.  At this point the person may have the energy to kill themselves.

SELF-DETERMINATION

Callers remain responsible for their lives and do not lose the right to make decisions even if that decision is to take their own life.

|Care plans and banned callers|See the green caller care folders. Also the whiteboard in the Ops room includes up-to-date details of banned callers and those on time-restricted plans.|
|Electric meter and key|Key 4 on the numbered rack. The meter cupboard is below the shelf of files, next to the desk in the office.|
|Gas meter, water meter and key|Key 1 on the numbered rack. The meter is by the outside door in the visitors' waiting room.|
|Keys to window locks|Key 5 on the numbered rack.|
|Store cupboard and key|Key 7 on the numbered rack. The cupboard is by the inside door of the visitors' waiting room. Contains additional stores of toilet rolls, food, cleaning materials etc.|
|Key to Ops room filing cabinet|On the numbered rack|
|Manuals for boiler, telephones, chairs etc|In red ring binder on the shelf in the office|
|Interview room alarm|Wall switch just inside the door|
|Personal alarm|On top of the pigeon holes|
|Dishwasher tablets, rubbish sacks, cleaning materials|In the cupboard under the kitchen sink.|
|Rubbish store for collection|In the open area of pavement just outside the interview room window, in Junction Rd.|
|Rubbish sacks, recycling box etc|Shredder bags are under the sink. The green recycling box is under the table in the Ops room. The plastics recycling bag is in the visitors' corridor. All are put on on Sunday pm.|
|Urgent maintenance problems|There is a 'Maintenance' pigeonhole for urgent requests. There is also a book, kept in the Ops room, to log problems. Steve 1143 is currently in charge of maintenance.|
|Suggestions book|On the shelf with the folders in the office.|
|Suicide in Progress / SIP alarms|There is a buzzer labelled SIP in each booth|
|Change of address/phone/email|There is a clipboard on the shelf under one of the office noticeboards, but please also alter your details on 3 Rings.|
|Recording outgoing phone calls|Small notebook on a hook above the desk in the Ops room|
|Cards to put out on the gate when the centre is closed|On a shelf above the CCTV unit|
|Mains light failure / kettle does not switch on|Check the fusebox in the electric meter cupboard in the office|
|Heating has gone off|''Please don't alter the programmer! ''The heating is on a timer, but if it is cold, you can boost it for a while by pressing the 'region 1 boost' switch on the unit on the kitchen wall, and turning the thermostat dial above the large shredder in the hall by the waiting room. Press start.|
|Bottled water|Spare bottles are in the hall, but if there are no spares, there's a label with the water company's number to call for spares. Please bear in mind our opening hours when ordering.|
|Shredder sack full|Switch off shredder, remove old bag and tie off. Put full bag in rubbish store. New bags are kept under the kitchen sink.|
|Ordering a taxi|There are a number of cards on one of the noticeboards in the office. Get a receipt from the driver and put a note in the treasurer's pigeonhole (Eileen 2688).|
|Checking office phone for messages|On arrival, and especially if the centre has been closed, check the office phone for messages.|
|Operating the CCTV|Instructions are taped to the CCTV unit. Please don't fiddle with the other buttons!|
|Booking a meeting room|Use the year-planner on the landing wall upstairs. First come first served.|
|Post|Usually sits on the shelf just inside the front door. You can sort it and put it into the relevant pigeonholes or just leave it.|

''Bomb Warnings''

KEY POINTS

* Take the message down WORD FOR WORD
* Get the exact location of the bomb (town, street etc.)
* REPEAT the message to the caller
* Note the exact time and length of the call, background noises, accent etc.
* Ring the police on 999 and pass on the message
* Contact the Leader and Director IMMEDIATELY
* Complete the [[bomb warning form|Bomb Warning Form.pdf]] and leave in Director’s pigeonhole

BOMB WARNINGS BY EMAIL OR TEXT:

* Print the email or text which makes the bomb warning.
* Ring the police on 999 and pass on the message.
* Contact the Leader and Director IMMEDIATELY.
* Complete the [[bomb warning form|Bomb Warning Form.pdf]] and leave in Director’s pigeonhole with the printout.

''Calling out an Ambulance''

* Your duty partner will ring the Leader and inform them that you have a [[SIP call|SIP - Suicide in Progress]].
* Find out if the Caller wants medical help. 
* If so, encourage them to call an ambulance themselves. 

''//If the Caller asks you to call an ambulance for them://''

Gently inform the Caller that if we or any third party rings for an ambulance for them, it is standard procedure for the London Ambulance Service to ask the Police to attend. 

IMPORTANT -  PLEASE NOTE

* It used to be the case that if the Caller called an ambulance themselves, police presence was avoided.
* This now appears to have changed (information has been checked with the Metropolitan Police February 2013)
* If the Ambulance service have previous Intel. (intelligence/knowledge) of the caller and they are concerned about what they will find on arrival, the Ambulance service will ask the police to attend.

''//If the Caller agrees to call the ambulance themselves://''

* Get the caller’s full address and telephone number.
* Reassure them that you will stay on the line with them while the ambulance arrives but ask them to put their front door on the latch.
* If appropriate offer a Follow Up call in a day or so.
* Try and talk to the ambulance team on their arrival and find out which hospital the caller is being taken to.

''//If the Caller wants us to call out an ambulance://'' 

Your partner will check with the Leader and if the Leader agrees you will need some details such as:

* Name of Caller
* Their address
* Their telephone number
* What they have done to themselves and/or taken

Whilst you remain with the Caller, your duty partner will now:

* Ring the number given by the caller to see if it is engaged
* Check their address in the A-Z / Google to see if it exists
* Ring the Leader with this information to ask for help, advice and a decision.
* The Leader may decide to come in to the Centre
* If necessary ring A&E at Ealing Hospital on 020 8967 5000 to find out the effect of the drugs taken and urgency of treatment required.
* If appropriate, offer a Follow Up call in a day or so.

Callers remain free to refuse an ambulance or to call one themselves.

If the caller has given us his/her details but has refused an ambulance and becomes unconscious or incapable of making a rational decision, by law we must call an ambulance and the caller must be advised that we will do so.

IF AT THIS POINT THE CALLER PUTS THE PHONE DOWN WE DO NOTHING

*

Calls from callers who have attempted suicide can be very traumatic for us. Be sure to talk things through with your Leader so you are reassured we did all we could. You may be called by your Leader later to see how you are feeling in the cold light of day. Sometimes calls like this can creep up on us days or weeks after the event. Be conscious of the support network sitting behind you and use it.

''Calls about Advertising or Fundraising Ideas''

Take their details and put a note in the Chairman's pigeonhole, or if for publicity, in Roger 1165's pigeonhole.







''Calls from Prison (update needed)''

Prison co-ordinators:

* Sue 836 - Feltham Young Offenders Institute,
* Robert 1035 - Wormwood Scrubs

Calls can be received from:

* Prisoners, Listeners or Prison Officers all in need of emotional support.
* Listeners (Wormwood Scrubs) who may wish to leave a message for the Prison co-ordinator 
* An inmate at Feltham A needing a visit. We visit Feltham on Tuesdays 18:00 – 20:00. Visits can be arranged on other days to suit the volunteer but always check with Sue 836. 


Key points:

* Befriend as usual anyone needing emotional support
* If a Listener from Wormwood Scrubs wishes to leave a message for the Prison team, please take the details and  ring or email Robert 1035 -  07792 165 477, or Robert.jackson2@gmail.com
* A Listener may want to debrief after a difficult call – support as you would a fellow volunteer. Inform Robert 1035 as above.
* A prison Officer may wish to pass a message to a prison co-ordinator take details and ring Sue or Robert as appropriate.
* A young offender may ask for a visit – check on the ‘prison board’ (in the office) that a volunteer is going to Feltham before taking details as below then ring or email Sue 836 on 020 8567 0367 or 07949 078 082, or suegreen2011@gmail.com  To pass a message to the prison co-ordinator – take caller’s name, prisoner number, which prison they are in and which wing they are on
* Do not take any messages from prisoners to be passed to a 3rd party e.g. a parent, sibling or solicitor 
* Do not offer to ring a prisoner back, it is not an option.  If the prisoner is in great distress he may ask to talk to his religious mentor, to Outreach or if he is in the adult section – to a Listener
* Log all calls.  Feltham calls need to be logged twice in log book and on the Feltham sheet.
* Thameside calls – please see bulletin on Prison Notice Board


Feltham Young Offenders Institute – This prison consists of 2 parts.

* Feltham A is for young offenders 14 – 18 years old.  They do not have access to Listeners so our volunteers visit and wing walk, talking in private, face to face with a prisoner.  Visits are usually on Tuesdays 18:00 – 20:00 but may be on another day to suit a Samaritan volunteer so please check on the prison board before offering a visit.  The wings visited are: Albatross, Bittern, Curlew, Dunlin, Eagle, Falcon, Jay and Heron.  Ibis is for prisoners needing psychiatric treatment.

* Feltham B is for adults, 18+.  They have access to Listeners so no visits.

Both prison teams would welcome interest from additional volunteers.  Contact Sue or Robert






''Complaints''

''KEY POINTS:''

* Listen calmly.
* Acknowledge the caller’s frustration
* Befriend if possible and reflect back what they are saying to you to make sure you have understood correctly
* Apologise

If the caller wants to take the complaint further:

* Tell the caller that complaints are dealt with by a branch director
* Try to discover if the caller knows which branch he/she spoke to and the name of the Samaritan volunteer
* Take the callers’ name and contact number and say that the director will call them back
* Put details in the director’s pigeonhole
                   
''EVERY COMPLAINT IS TAKEN __SERIOUSLY__''

Sometimes a caller may feel they want to complain about the support they have received from us. It is very important to take all complaints seriously and to treat the caller with courtesy, empathy and respect, whatever the nature of their complaint.

Always try and develop calls which are presented as complaints. Often such complaints are a ‘way in’ to callers wanting to talk about their problems.

All branches follow the same procedure, ensuring consistency. All complaints must be investigated fully and sympathetically and in accordance with Samaritans’ complaint procedures.

In certain cases, if the complaint is particularly serious, it may need to be dealt with by Head Office as a movement-wide issue, take all details and pass them to our Director, who decides whether to pass the complaint on.

Occasionally, the complainant will not wish to give their name and phone number but will wish to take their complaint directly to General Office themselves.  Please give the caller the number – 020 8394 8300 - brief the Leader and leave details in the Director’s pigeonhole.

''Data Protection, Record Keeping and Honesty Policy''

''POLICY'' “Samaritans publicly state how information relating to callers is used”.

KEY POINTS:

* If a caller asks about confidentiality, reassure them that “everything is confidential within Samaritans”.  Never promise one-to-one confidentiality between you and the caller
* We need to ask the caller’s permission to keep notes on file.  See below.
* If the caller asks us not to keep records, explain that we always log each call, but if the caller wishes it can be destroyed after it has been reviewed. Such records are shredded regularly
* If a caller asks to see the records we keep, explain that we have a strict procedure for this and that the caller will have to apply in writing to the branch Director.  
* If possible get the caller’s contact details and say that someone will be in touch to explain the process.  Do not give out any details over the phone.
* Inform the Leader and leave the caller’s details in the Director’s pigeonhole 

We need to take great care how we disclose information so that we do not disclose information about other callers, and must make as certain as possible that we have matched our notes with the caller.  Hence the strict procedure.

Asking callers if we can keep notes can be difficult and uncomfortable but must be done according to data legislation. Possible ways:

* Would you mind if I keep a note of this here? 
* Are you happy for us to hang onto the details whilst you are going through such a bad time?
* It would help us to help you if we had a few notes of what you said so that volunteers on other shifts understand what you are going through?  Is that OK?
* Do you have any objections to us hanging onto these details?
* You’ve told me lots, is it OK if we keep a note of things so that if you ring again someone will know your story?
* We do keep records but they are confidential to us in the same way that everything you have told me is confidential within Samaritans.








''Diversity and Equality''

''Our Diversity and Equality policy helps us to:''

* Make sure that we recruit and retain the very best volunteers and staff from a wide variety of sources.
* Value our volunteers and staff and the differences between them.
* Harness those differences to improve our service to callers.
* Promote diversity and equality in a proactive way to underpin our service to the callers.
* Make sure that all our policies, procedures and working practices are free from any form of unlawful or unfair discrimination.

''In carrying this out, we will:''

* Eliminate any harassment or unjustifiable discrimination against anyone for any reason, including their race, colour, nationality, ethnic or national origin, religion, sex or sexual orientation, working pattern, marital status, gender reassignment, disability, age political opinion or family status.
* Make sure the policy is effective by making it include all areas of our work.
* Make sure that we make every effort to achieve equality of access to all sites used by Samaritans.
* Ask branches to review regularly their activities in the light of the need to achieve the Diversity and Equality Policy.
* Display the policy on all premises and sites used by Samaritans.

''Rules of behaviour:''

The rules of behaviour should be viewed as part of our commitment to eliminate discrimination and harassment against individuals and particular groups set out above.

''The following types of behaviour are unacceptable:''

* Attacks on individuals or groups on the basis of their race, gender, ethnic origin, disability or sexual orientation.
* Discriminatory name-calling, insulting remarks, jokes or threats.

''Ending Calls''


Ending calls can be hard, but remember:

* Callers can ring us back and if they have had a good contact, almost certainly will do so. 

* Long calls make the caller and you tired – you both need a break and a chance to reflect.

KEY POINTS:

* Ending calls is a necessary part of what we do, but never rush an ending. How you end a call is important. A clumsy ending may undo all the time, empathy and understanding that you have given to the caller, so make sure that feelings have been fully explored (especially suicidal feelings) and the caller feels they can call back if they need to. 

* Use the skills you have learnt – Revisit the [[Listening Wheel|The Listening Wheel]] e.g. summarise and reflect back to the caller what has been said.

* Calls that are repetitive or go round in circles should be ended – they could be stopping others from getting through. Take charge of the call. Summarise what the caller has told you and ask if there is anything else worrying them.

* If caller will not talk about feelings, is drunk or under the influence of drugs and unable/unwilling to accept emotional support take charge of the call and end it.

* Do a ‘mental review’ after a call has reached 30 minutes. Ask yourself:

** Is continuing the call adding anything?
** What should we use the rest of the call to achieve?
** Should I flag up timing to the caller and ask what they would like the rest of the call to explore?
** Should I summarise the main points of the call and suggest time for reflection?

* If you are struggling to end a call, ask your shift partner for help

* If appropriate [[offer Follow Up|Offering Follow-Up Calls]], but only in exceptional circumstances – e.g. a caller at risk of suicide in distress or despair. In most circumstances, it is better to suggest that a caller rings back having considered the options you have discussed.

* Wait to hear the caller put the phone down before you do so. Caller may feel rejected if the Samaritan is the first to put the phone down – exception sex and abusive callers after the warning has been given.

* Make sure we are not being used as a chat line.

* Check if the caller is limited to one call/a timed call per day and has already been in contact.

''How do we say goodbye? Some suggestions:''

* "We have talked for some time now, and examined a number of options. Why don't you think about the points we have covered? If you need to talk some more, you can always phone us back."
* "You know that we are available 24/7, so there is always someone to listen to you."
* "How are you feeling now?"
* "You seem more relaxed..."
* "You sound much calmer now. Has talking clarified things for you?"
* "What will you do next?"
* "Would it help to...? / Would it help if...?"
* "How would you feel about visiting your local Samaritans branch? Do you think it would be of help to you?"
* "Do you often call Samaritans? Does it help? How does it help?
* "How do you think Samaritans can help you with this problem?"
* "I think we have spoken before..."
* "When we last spoke..."






''Ending Inappropriate Calls''

''Ending sex calls'' (1 warning then end the call):

* "Are you feeling suicidal?"
* "Samaritans offer emotional support to people who are suicidal or in emotional distress or despair. As you are not willing to talk about your feelings, I am going to end this call now."
* "I can't talk to you while you are masturbating. You can always ring back when you are able to talk about your feelings. I am going to end this call now."

''Abusive callers'' (2 warnings then end the call)

''Banned callers:''

* "You have been told that Samaritans are unable to help you and that you should not be ringing us." //Please do not say "you are a banned caller."//






''Enquiries from Police, Press, Media''

Take the caller’s name and contact number and say that someone will get back to them.

Ring and/or email the contact details to the Director also put a copy of the details in the Director’s pigeonhole

Log the call

Inform the Leader







''Enquiries from Potential Volunteers'' or confirmation of attendance at initial training

Explore the nature of the call and befriend if appropriate.

Ask which branch the caller wishes to volunteer for.

''EALING BRANCH: ''

* Take their name, phone number and email address and write them into the PV selection book.  
* For Ealing PVs, always try to get an email address as this is the easiest and cheapest form of contact.
* Give the caller the date and times of our next selection days (see the white board).
* Explain that an Invitation Pack will be sent  giving them details of the timetable for the day, a general introductory letter and a map giving directions to the centre.
* Tea, coffee, water and biscuits are provided, but it is advisable to bring a sandwich for lunch.
''
OTHER BRANCHES:''

* Take name, phone number and email address.
* Look in the CONFIDENTIAL section of the Branch Reference File (black folder on shelf above electricity meter) for the office number of the branch the caller wishes to join. Ring that number and give details or leave a message.
* Tell the caller that you will pass their details to their chosen branch and that someone will be in touch with them.

''Face to Face Visitors''

Advice from Council of Samaritans and the Board of Trustees:

<<<
Face to Face is conducted in the visitors interview room, behind closed doors so that the caller has privacy in the same way that he or she has privacy when making a phone call or sending an email. The personal security and safety of volunteers is paramount and should take precedence over the needs of the visitor.
<<<

''Key points''

* If both volunteers are on the phone when the visitor rings the bell, remember that the most important caller is the one you are speaking to on the phone.
** If one of the phone calls has run its course, gently end it.
* Change your connect status to "not available for calls".
* Look at the CCTV picture to see if you recognise the visitor. Then speak to him or her, through the intercom if you wish.
* If you recognise the visitor as a ''banned caller'':
** Phone the leader.
** Inform the visitor via the intercom that we are unable to help and that he or she should leave.
* Otherwise, ask the visitor to wait a moment while you phone the leader.
** If the visitor is very distressed, ask your partner to phone the leader instead.
* Welcome the visitor. Make eye contact straight away. If it feels comfortable, give your name and ask for theirs. It is important that we put the visitor at ease from the moment we open the door.
* Show the visitor to the interview room. Be aware of their body language, without making assumptions.
** Use caution about allowing visitors to bring anything into the room you feel uncomfortable with. However, it is not appropriate to ask a distressed visitor to leave her handbag behind!
* Offer a drink. If they accept, this also gives you time to check the green Caller Care file to see if there's any information there about the visitor.
* Throughout the visit, maintain appropriate eye contact. Take your cue from the visitor as some people find too much eye contact intimidating. 
* Concentrate on feelings and (as on the phone) explore suicidal feelings.
* Avoid physical contact with the visitor. A handshake, only if offered by the visitor, may be acceptable.
* ''Important'': the other Samaritan on duty should check that all is well after no more than 20 minutes. 
** An easy way to do this: knock on the door, apologise for the disturbance and say that you need a quick word with your colleague.
** This allows your colleague to leave the room and say whether they are comfortable continuing or not.
* If there is ''any problem or anxiety'', at any point, excuse yourself and ring the leader for advice. 
* ''If the visitor becomes angry or abusive '' - stay calm and do not get angry back. If they do not calm down, you may ask him or her to leave the branch.
* It is the visitor's right to leave at any time and thus end the visit.
* At the end of the visit, call the leader and log the visit using Connect.

''Making Follow-Up Calls''

KEY POINTS: 

* Log the call, remember to tick Follow Up offered (O) and accepted (A) boxes and check in the green Caller file if the caller has called recently. Write up the caller in the green Caller Care file.   
* Write time of call and caller’s name on the relevant page of the diary and his/her phone number ''on a post it note'' and stick in the diary. ''Do not write personal details directly into the diary.''
* If Follow Up is offered but rejected, still fill in the Follow Up offered column in the log
''* Never write a caller’s history in the diary, just the name and the telephone number separately on a post it note.''






''Mission, Vision and Values''

''Samaritans' vision is that fewer people die by suicide''

* We work to achieve this Vision by making it our ''Mission'' to alleviate emotional distress and reduce the incidence of suicidal feelings and suicidal behaviour.

We do this by:

* ''Being available 24 hours a day to provide emotional support'' for people who are experiencing feelings of emotional distress or despair, including those which may lead to suicide.
* ''Reaching out to high risk groups and communities'' to reduce the risk of suicide.
* ''Working in partnership'' with other organisations, agencies and experts to achieve our Vision.
* ''Influencing public policy and raising awareness'' of the challenges of reducing suicide.

We are committed to the following ''Values'':

* ''Listening'' – because exploring feelings alleviates distress and helps people to reach a better understanding of their situation and the options open to them.
* ''Confidentiality'' – because if people feel safe, they are more likely to be open about their feelings.
* ''People making their own decisions wherever possible'' because we believe that people have the right to find their own solution and telling people what to do takes responsibility away from them.
* ''Being Non-Judgemental'' –  accepting people for who they are because we want people to be able to talk to us without fear of prejudice or rejection.
* ''Human Contact'' – because giving people time, undivided attention and empathy meets a fundamental emotional need and reduces distress and despair.

(from The Samaritans’ Strategy 2015)

Dear Ealing Sams


You might be interested in this statistic…

!! Within the London region, our branch is second in terms of the number of calls handled.

It’s a great result – and proof that we’re not just about quality, but quantity as well! 

[img[pic001.png]] 

For reference, Central London (which is obviously a very different sort of branch and on a different scale – it costs £500,000 a year to run) handled 7836 calls in the same period. 

Anna 464 / Charles 1133







''Offering Follow-Up Calls''

This is a specific offer made to the caller that a Samaritan will contact the caller within an agreed time span.  It is NOT an offer to the caller to ring us again if he/she feels the need to do so.

When the caller is in crisis, it is always appropriate to initiate Follow Up. Follow Up can be a very powerful way of letting callers know that we care and are with them through their difficult times.  Callers tell us that they really appreciate the knowledge that someone is going to call them – it makes them feel less alone.

Be careful not to use the offer of a call back as a way of ending a call.   This can push a problem you are trying to avoid onto another volunteer, it is not the best use of call backs and is ultimately not fair on the caller.

KEY POINTS: Offer Follow Up if: 

* If the caller is at active risk of suicide / is self-harming
* Has attempted suicide, but has called an ambulance
* Is very deeply depressed and is not coping
* Has been recently bereaved or is facing an anniversary of bereavement
* Is anticipating bad news or a traumatic event in the near future
* Can’t get through the day or the night
* Lacks the will or self-confidence to make another call
* Your feeling is that the caller requires a Follow up call
* If a caller refuses a Follow-up call, encourage the caller to stay in contact, explain the availability of the Samaritans service and if appropriate, offer them the number of their local branch. 

INFORMATION YOU NEED TO OBTAIN: Try not to make this a barrage of questions:

* Caller’s name and telephone number.
* Day/date/ of call back. Check that the centre is open.  
* Time of call back – promises on time cannot be too specific 
* Does the caller have anonymous number call barring?  This will have to be removed as Samaritans have their number withheld.
* Is there an answer phone as we will not leave a message unless arranged with the caller.
* Is there likely to be anyone else there?
* If someone else answers the phone what would the caller like us to say? Eg. – “It’s a friend, I will ring later”

The volunteer offering the follow up call must explain that another volunteer will be contacting the caller but does not give a specific name or a precise time.

Also see the procedure to follow when [[Making Follow-Up Calls]].

''Police Calls about Bailed Prisoners''

Before a person leaves a Police Station (normally on bail) they are asked to complete a form.  The form lists several agencies, of which we are one.

If they tick the Samaritans box, the police will ring us with the name and phone number of the person concerned, so that we can call him or her.


* We should try to phone twice. 

* If there’s no answer, we should NOT leave a message.

* After two attempts, we do not try again.


This only happens very rarely, but we should all be aware of the agreed procedure.

These are recorded on Three Rings|

(If you prefer to split Night Watches, you need to do an equal number of 1.00 - 4.00 and 4.00 -7.00 sessions) <br><br>//''There are no age or lifelong exemptions from unsocial hours shifts''//|

''Reverse Charge Calls''

It costs £50 to accept a reverse charge call for a minimum of 10 minutes.  There are callers who make malicious reverse charge calls costing branches literally thousands of pounds. 

We should only accept reverse charges as a last resort, under the following conditions:

# When we can talk to the operator, ie. no automated calls
# After directing the caller to the Freecall number 116 123
# When we are satisfied the caller is in crisis

If in doubt, do not accept the call.  Don’t forget the Leader is there for guidance.

If you do accept the call, keep it short and offer to ring the caller back preferably on a land line. 

Record the call and its duration in the usual way as well as in the book of calls dialled out by us.  







''Samaritans' Basic Guidelines''

|DO|DON'T|
|Actively listen - use the listening wheel<br>Be confidential<br>Be honest <br>Talk about feelings <br>Always explore suicidal thoughts / feelings <br> Remain calm |Give advice / opinions <br>Talk about yourself <br>Make assumptions / be judgemental <br> Make promises <br> Lend money <br>Be afraid of silences <br>Talk to the police / press|

1. __Please note - new approach.__ Asking "are you feeling suicidal?" can feel quite brutal. Often it is more gentle to reflect and clarity the caller's own words to see if the caller is feeling suicidal. "When you say you have had enough..."

2. Promote the positive benefits of contacting us rather than saying what we can't do.

3. Stress that Samaritans are there for anyone in distress / despair, not just for callers who are suicidal.

4. Our mission is to reduce suicide. Therefore we work with callers to help them to find a way of living rather than dying. Ultimately, if the caller wants to die then we respect that decision - see the rebalanced self-determination policy.

''SIGNPOSTING''

''POLICY:  ''Samaritans believes that the caller is the expert on their own life.  Signposting provide callers with the option of contacting other services that may help them increase their options of practical or emotional support.

The volunteer if asked or thinks it will benefit the caller may provide details for other organisations that may be able to provide additional support to that offered by Samaritans 

KEY POINTS:

* Befriend the caller.  Listen and offer emotional support
* Explore options available
* Explore suicidal feelings
* The caller may ask for an organisation which may help with a specific problem eg. “do you know who could help sort out my visa problems?”  Volunteer gives the caller the number for Advice at Ealing 
* The caller may ask for the number/address of a specific organisation. If available, we give it to the caller
* During the call, having explored the caller’s feelings and listening to their concerns it becomes obvious to the volunteer that there is another organisation that can offer the caller more specialist help, again we give the number
* Whenever information about another organisation is given out, we must inform the caller that we do not know the quality of help provided and whether they will be able to provide the assistance which the caller requires / is looking for.

''Silent Calls''

As you pick up the phone you may immediately hear the caller put their phone down.  This is a snap call and is logged as such. A snap call is also one when the caller says a few words and then hangs up.

You may pick the phone up and not hear the click at the other end, you may have a silent call where the caller is reluctant to speak, but retains the contact and it is our task to encourage the caller to speak. 

There are many reasons why the caller may be reluctant to talk e.g. 

•	Not ready to talk
•	Just wants to hear a human
•	Too frightened to talk
•	Too upset
•	Not sure how to begin

We encourage the caller to speak by gentle, quiet encouragement, don’t be afraid of silences, long pauses may encourage the caller to start talking – nervous gabbling will not.  The way you respond will determine whether the caller ever talks about his/her problem.  Do not be distressed or disappointed if the caller hangs up without saying a word.  It is well known that distressed callers may call a number of times before saying a word.

Remember – your caller has made the first step and has made contact.  You may be the only person he/she has ever tried to tell, so the way in which you respond may determine if the caller will ever talk about what is troubling them.

The call could run as follows - the following are suggestions, not a script to be learnt and repeated by rote.  You must be yourself and mean what you say.

*

Samaritans – can I help you

Pause – caller remains silent

Repeat, but differently – e.g. “You are through to Samaritans – can I help you.” This confirms that the caller has the correct number and you don’t sound like a robot

Pause – the caller still does not answer.  From now on make the pauses longer

Reassure the caller – e.g. “there is no rush, I am here to listen when you are ready to talk” or “whatever you say to me is confidential within Samaritans” or “ it is a safe place to talk because…..” or “take your time”

Repeat the reassuring line / pause cycle a few times.  This should reassure the caller that it is OK not to speak until he/she is ready – no pressure

Gently ask a closed question.  “did you ring us today because you are feeling suicidal?”  You are now putting pressure on the caller to respond

Pause – make it a short one as there is a risk that the caller will put the phone down

Another reassuring line

Pause

Another closed question

You may want to repeat the pause-reassurance-pause-closed question sequence

After about 10 - 15 minutes ask the caller to tap the phone or make some audible sign that they are still there

Pause. If there is still no response, begin to end the call.  Here, tone of voice is very important. The caller must feel that he/she is very welcome to ring again when ready to speak.

E.g.” you seem to be finding it difficult to talk at the moment, I would like to listen to what is troubling you now, but if you can’t talk, perhaps we should take a break and you can call us back whenever you feel ready to talk. There is someone to listen to you 24/7 “

Pause – still no response

“I am going to put the phone down now. Take care of yourself.  Goodbye.”








''SIP - Suicide in Progress''

KEY POINTS

* Remember: Never take a major decision on your own.
* Use the back-up team of duty partner, Day or Night Leader and/or Duty Director.
* The Leader and Duty Director may be contacted at any time of the day or night.
* Be sure to talk things through afterwards.

PROCEDURE DURING A SUICIDE IN PROGRESS (SIP) CALL

* As soon as you are certain that your caller has tried to take their own life, signal to your partner on duty that you will need support.  Use the SIP buzzer in your booth.
* Try to find out from the Caller what they have done/taken. 
* If possible get the name of the chemical or medicine.
* Keep contact with and support the Caller at all times.
* Your partner will call the Duty Leader who will remain in contact throughout.

Read on to find out more about [[Calling out an Ambulance]].

''ARE YOU FEELING SUICIDAL? YES! What can we say next?''

* Are you saying that you want to die?
* Are you on your own?<br><br>
* What are you feeling when you say that to me? / What feelings are in your mind now?
* How long have you been feeling like this?
* How often do you think about it?
* Would it help to describe what has got you to this point?
* What happened to make you feel like this?<br><br>
* Do you want to die for ever?
* What plan do you have / have you made?
* Have you started to put your plan into action?<br><br>
* Have you attempted suicide before?
* If so, would it help to describe how it felt?
* How do you imagine it on the other side? / What does death mean to you?
* What do you expect death to be like for you?
* What do you think it would be like to be dying?<br><br>
* Why do you see this as an option?
* Have you considered other options?
* Is there anything you want to live for? / Is there anything you would miss?<br><br>
* Have you been close to someone who has died? What / how did you feel?
* What would you like to happen to your body after death?
* How do you envisage your funeral? What plans have you made for your funeral?<br><br>
* How are you feeling now?

''Support After a Difficult Call''

''//Getting Support on Shift//''

* The first port of call for support on shift is your Leader. 
* They are there to support and guide you through difficult calls and to give you the opportunity to fully debrief after the call.
* You can approach the Leader at any time during the shift if you have something you need to talk about or that is on your mind.
* Other routes of support on shift besides the Leader are your partner on duty and the Duty Deputy Director.
* One of the most important sources of support are your fellow volunteers and your Group Leader – we are all here to help and should be prepared to listen to each other as much as to our callers.

''//What if something stays with me after the shift?//''

* Sometimes a call will stay with you, either straight after a shift or some time later. The principle remains that we are all here for each other. 
* You should feel able to contact any Samaritan with whom you feel comfortable discussing the call. This can be a Leader, Duty Director, your Group Leader,  someone from your training group or any volunteer you feel comfortable talking to.
* You can call anytime, don’t worry about disturbing people. If someone is not able to talk at that moment, they will say so and suggest another convenient time.
* The important thing is never to feel that you have to keep things bottled up. We all experience calls which affect us – saying so is certainly not a sign of weakness.
* The reverse side of this is that you should consider it part of your commitment to support your colleagues through difficulties they are experiencing.

''Technical notes:''

Software

* This wiki uses Tiddywiki 5 ('TW5') open source software - see http://tiddlywiki.com for details and guidelines on how to use it.
* The client file is automatically updated through github and readers can access it through a web browser at http://bit.ly/ealingsams. For the sake of security, the id and password for updating the file are kept separately.
* The master/server file is kept separate by Charles 1133, and currently backed up using dropbox (automatically) and a hard drive offsite (manually).
 
The ''sources of information'' so far loaded are:

 
* Procedures: from Krys 2042 and her team (thank you all!)
* SIT 1 materials: from the 2015 pdfs published on Samaritans Net.

It may be possible to add further information sources in future, with two major barriers:

* Table layouts are a bit painful (see my remark below)
* Data protection rules stop us loading some classes of information.  In this cases, we will attempt to load the information onto Samsnet and link to them from here.

''Viewing information''

* The menu structure is provisional and is fairly easy to change / improve. It is alphabetical by default.
* The best way to read this wiki is in a browser on a desktop or laptop - Chrome or Firefox preferred. (You may not see all pdf pages on mobiles and tablets.) 
* This does NOT always work on Microsoft's Internet Explorer - pdfs don't display properly and some versions even block the site as being unsafe (erroneously).

''Uploading information''

* Text information is easy to upload and format. Firstly, you create a new topic (known in TW5 as a 'tiddler') then just type or copy in the text. Then TW5 uses Wiki Text - simple commands to allow ''bold'', //italics//, __underlines__, bullets, numbering, links and so on. 
* Information in tables is a bit painful, and not WYSIWYG (What you see is what you get). See [[London Branches|London Branches]] and open it with the pen symbol to see how the notation works.
* It is possible to upload pdfs, including multi-page pdfs. See [[Nature of Service|Nature of Service.pdf]] for an example. The SIT materials are in big pdfs and really have to be broken down into individual subjects to make them easily accessible. I have tested this by loading them into Chrome (on a Mac) and printing off subsets of pages into smaller pdfs. This is time consuming, but doesn't have to be done often.
* We can update picture files on a one-by-one basis and include them in articles. An example is the map in [[London Branches|London Branches]].
 
''Printing'' 

* You can print ''most'' topics by clicking on the button in the top right, next to the title. (''Very'' technical note: [[See here for the before and after|Technical Note 2 - editing the print button and text]].)
* Some topics are really ''pdfs''. Normally, they will have .pdf at the end of the topic name. There's a black box around the pdf which includes a menu option for printing. (You can print these in some browsers but not others. Firefox or Chrome seem to be fine - But it doesn't appear in Internet Explorer on Windows or Safari on a Mac.)






''Terrorist Activity (2015)''

Terrorism can be broadly defined as:

“Any activity, which involves serious violence or use of explosives, which is designed to influence the government or intimidate the public”.

We are legally required to report to the police any information we have which relates to terrorist activities. 

KEY POINTS

* A caller who decides to talk to Samaritans about terrorist activities may do so assuming that the conversation will be treated in the same confidential manner as all our other contacts. THIS IS NOT THE CASE.
* The volunteer should interrupt the caller who begins to talk about terrorist activity and inform the caller that we are not legally able to treat such information in confidence and that anything the caller says may be passed to the authorities. 
* The caller then has the choice to continue the call or to hang up.
* Immediately the call ends the Leader must be contacted for advice and guidance.

''Third Party Referrals''

This is a specific request by a caller to contact another person (a third party) who they feel is very distressed or suicidal.

KEY POINTS:

* The caller making the contact should be offered emotional support in the same way as any other caller
* Try to get the following information from the caller:
** Their name and telephone number.
** Their relationship with the person they want us to call.
** Potential suicide risk of the person they wish us to call and any other background information.
** The name and phone number of the person to call, and whether we should leave a message – is the phone shared, does the 3rd party have call barring?
** Will the third party be expecting a call from Samaritans?
* Throughout your conversation try to gauge if the call is genuine and not malicious.
* Ask the caller if we may say to the third party that the contact was initiated by them.
* Go over the following points with the caller:
** We will not promise to make the call but we will consider the request and if the caller wishes we will let them know if we have not made contact.
** We will not discuss with the caller any aspect of our contact without the permission of the third party.
* Write up the call in the log and in the green caller care file. 
* CONTACT THE LEADER FOR ADVICE
* If the call is to be made enter the details in the diary (as for Follow up) and label it as a 3rd party call

We will usually accept third party calls, but'' it is the Leader who decides'' and he/she will have to make some checks to avoid hoaxes, which are very damaging both to the person being called as well as to our reputation.

If the call is to be made immediately, the Leader may advise that the duty colleague should make the call.   If the call is to be made some time later it must be entered in the diary and labelled as a third party call.

If there is no reply, Samaritans should try twice more at intervals and report no reply to the Leader, who may advise the original Samaritan to let the original caller know that we have been unable to contact the third party.










''DOCUMENTATION PROJECT''

''The problems we’ve tried to solve''

# Volunteers don’t always know procedures.  (Sometimes procedures change, sometimes we just get rusty.)
# Printed information may be out of date.
# Information is in many different places. 
# It’s hard to disseminate news and updates to volunteers across the branch.

[img[Booth Photo.jpg]]

//Within one booth we have notices about opening hours, hot lists, debriefing procedures, passwords, Connect server update, signposting... as well as folders. //

''What we would like to have instead (the vision for this project):''

# A way for volunteers to access relevant information very fast, while on a call.
# A definitive source of the latest version of any document.
# A single store for much of our information, which is easy to retrieve and print.
# A way for us to highlight news (including new or changed procedures) to all volunteers, while they are on shift.

... legally and ethically compliant...
… and preferably for free …


''What stood in our way?''

* ''Bad software'' – the software on 3rings is just not up to the job. Filestore is chaotic and the wiki is inadequate. Plenty of us have tried to make it work, and there are some valuable documents on there, but it’s pushing water uphill. If you want something in filestore, there's no way of searching for it. You have (a) to figure out where in the menu to look (b) guess which file it’s in (c) download the file (d) open it in other software - and then find out whether the information is there or not. Lots of information is missing, none of it is in order, and some of it is out of date.
 
* ''Overwhelm'' – the Samsnet software is a bit better. But firstly it’s very specialised – there’s a steep learning curve for setting up a branch space, let alone a menu and a wiki. Also there’s just too much information in Samsnet - some great information and plenty that's irrelevant. If you’re on a shift and you want to know how to handle a call from the police, there are 308 search results for ‘police’. There are 1561 results for ‘opening hours’. There's a potentially fantastic branch reference file (https://www.samaritansnet.org/display/RESOURCES/Branch+Reference+File) and operations manual (https://www.samaritansnet.org/display/OpsManual/Operations+Manual) but no-one knows about them, they're huge, and much of the information is out of date.  Navigation is hopeless. It’s also very hard to alert users to branch issues of current interest.

* ''Poor structure'' – we lack a single consistent menu for our documentation, together with clarity about who is responsible for what. See [[here|Possible Menu Structure]] for a high level proposal of how this could work for our branch.


''What do other branches do?''

I asked a question on Samsnet and no-one seems to have solved this.

* Most try to use 3rings and a few try samsnet – with the same problems we face.
* At least one branch has used Microsoft Office 365 software to create a database – this is quite specialist.
* At least one branch has a comprehensive word document of procedures which they update continuously.

These last two are similar to this proposal, but just use different software. I don’t think we have legal copies of Microsoft Office (including Word) on our PCs and they would cost money.


''Approach''

''We have created a new branch wiki,'' using Tiddlywiki5 software. It is well-established, free and easy to use. It also works on our PCs, using chrome as a preferred browser.  

''What were the biggest challenges to this approach?''

* Were we prepared to create a whole new source of information – away from 3rings and Samsnet?  

* What are the data protection & security implications?  Where caller and volunteer data are concerned, we will include links to specific documents on Samsnet, which requires ID and passwords to access.



''Advantages of the new wiki over 3rings and Samsnet''

* It’s much easier to use.
* It’s much simpler to administer.
* It's much easier to find information and print it out when we need it.
* It’s easier to stop people inadvertently messing up our information.
* Unlike Samsnet, we can include just information which our branch needs.
* I’ve shown it to a handful of volunteers on shift, and they’ve all loved it.


''Disadvantages of the new wiki versus 3rings and Samsnet''

* Loading word documents into the wiki may change the formatting, and it takes a minute or two to correct each document. Tables are particularly troublesome. (There is an alternative - turning the word file into a pdf - which means loading takes a little longer.)


''Reassurances''

* This doesn't mean we can't also have paper copies.
* The software works in a browser, just like 3rings and Samsnet.
* It works on our PCs despite the fact that our operating systems (Windows Vista, Windows 7) are old and no longer supported by Microsoft.
* It’s free.

''Young Callers''

Key points

Alert the Leader immediately if a visitor is under 16.

Explain our confidentiality policy in language the caller can understand: we do not breach the caller’s confidentiality, even if they are under 16

Befriend, using our listening skills in order to help them talk about their emotions

If the caller tells you things you feel should be reported (e.g. abuse) encourage and help the caller to see the options open to them, without being directive.  Encourage the caller to contact Childline. 

Debrief fully with the Leader – these calls can be harrowing

*

We need to be especially careful when dealing with young callers, not just because they are so vulnerable but also because of our duty of care and legislation which places the emphasis on the safety and wishes of the child. Our national policy is that 

<<<

“Samaritans will respect the rights of children to the same level of confidentiality as adult callers, subject to the provisions of any legislation which might require disclosure to be made.”
<<<


Often young callers need a lot of reassurance –

* about confidentiality, 
* that it is OK to ring about whatever they are ringing about, 
* that you believe them, that you understand dilemmas they may have (such as talking critically about a parent or carer), 
* that their feelings are understandable and that we know how hard it is for them to talk about private things.

A first call might concentrate on winning their trust with only short bursts of befriending and this can feel frustrating. Remember that they might be speaking for the first time about what is troubling them and they might find this difficult. Our aim is to reassure them so they will want to ring again – and do so. It is not to solve their problem or crisis immediately, not least as they are unlikely to want to move that fast.

If you find it hard to befriend young callers, talk to your leader, who will guide you through what can seem like a minefield.
